observations.recommendation:
1. Direct the Inventory Committee to facilitate the conduct of complete physical count of all the Municipality’s properties annually and prepare and submit the RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;
2. Require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain property records for all PPE and undertake the required reconciliation of the Property and Accounting records thereafter;
3. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare SLs and lapsing schedule for all PPE accounts and make the necessary adjustments to come up with the correct PPE accounts balances; and
4. Facilitate the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances through the implementation of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

11. Prioritize issuance of demand letters to all accountable officers and employees to immediately liquidate/settle their outstanding cash advances;
12. Require the Municipal Accountant to stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those who have unliquidated cash advances and strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances;
13. Fast track the recovery of the documents relevant to the long outstanding cash advances and conduct verification, analysis and validation to determine the settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted; and
14. Conform with the procedures and requirements set forth in COA Circular No. 2016-005 and immediately facilitate the request for write-off of dormant unliquidated cash advances.

22. Direct the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of inventory count of all the local roads and prepare and submit the RPCLRN;
23. Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Inventory Committee with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects to facilitate the preparation of RPCLRN; and
24. Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and maintain separate SLs/LRNLCs and LRNPCs, respectively, for local road projects and reconcile both records to ensure proper recording and control of the assets;
25. Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and submit the RLRN and Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and
26. Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component of road network, make necessary adjustments to correct the unrecorded depreciation expense as of year-end and provide proper and complete disclosure of the total road networks in the Notes to FS in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2015-008.

55. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly account for the acquisition and issuance of the supplies and materials inventory by adopting the Perpetual Inventory System and making the necessary adjustments to reflect the correct balance of the affected inventory and expense accounts;
56. Require all the Inventory Custodians to ensure that all issuances of supplies and materials are covered by RIS and the Municipal Treasurer to use the RIS as basis for the preparation of the SSMI. Also, instruct the Municipal Treasurer to submit the SSMI to the Municipal Accountant together with the original copies of the RIS which will be the basis of the latter to record in the books the expended portions of supplies and materials;
57. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to conduct periodic physical count of all supplies and materials on hand, submit the required RPCI and coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the same with the accounting records; and
58. Require the MT and the Municipal Accountant to properly maintain, update and reconcile the stock cards and SLCs, respectively.

65. Allocate adequate budget for the titling of its land properties in the name of the Municipality to establish absolute ownership and reduce the risk of third-party claims;
66. Require the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Assessor for the conduct of reconciliation of the accounting records with the actual land records of land owned by the LGU, make necessary adjustments, if warranted and prepare and maintain subsidiary records and RPLC for the Land account; and
67. Submit the lacking documentary requirements cited in the foregoing discussion and ensure strict compliance on the completeness of the supporting documentary requirements on subsequent transactions before every DV be approved for payment in order to ascertain the propriety and validity of all claims against the agency funds.

We recommended that Management:
Prepare a plan that specifies the timeline for accounting for specific PPE and identifies the responsible persons to implement all the recommendations below.
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to maintain PPE Ledger Cards and Local Road Network Ledger Cards, and Property Cards, respectively, for all roads and their components, with complete details and description;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for all existing road projects;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record the donated Patient Transport Vehicle received by the LGU, along with the corresponding depreciation expense for CY 2024; and
Direct the Municipal Administrator to coordinate with the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to initiate compliance with the guidelines and procedures for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account balances.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
File a request for write-off of the dormant receivable and liability accounts totaling ₱484,864.92, in accordance with the prescribed guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2023-008 dated August 17, 2023;
Exert more effort in retrieving the necessary documents to enforce the collection of receivable accounts amounting to ₱1,242,792.06, and issue demand letters to the concerned individuals and various associations;
Coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer to return the balances from program implementation to the source agencies under the Due to NGAs account;
Recognize the balances from the shares of tobacco excise taxes as income in the General Fund books, in the amounts of ₱15,452.00 and ₱1,000.00, which were recorded under the Due to NGAs account in the Trust Fund and the Trust Liabilities in the GF, respectively;
Transfer the Trust Liabilities-DRRMF under the GF, amounting to ₱304,169.01, to the Special Trust Fund for DRRMF in the TF books, which will be programmed as part of the funds to be included in the LDRRMF Investment Plan; and
Prepare a quarterly monitoring report and aging of receivables, which shall serve as the basis for issuing demand letters to ensure timely collection of receivables and liquidation of cash advances and fund transfers.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to record the:

Advance payments for RPT and SET as income when they are actually earned;




Discounts granted for prompt payment of property taxes due for the year as Discount on Real Property Tax – Basic or Discount on Special Education Tax;

Discounts given to taxpayer for paying property tax in advance as Discount on Advance Payments;

Collections on penalties from delinquent property taxes as Tax Revenue - Fines and Penalties – Property Taxes; and

Proposed adjusting entries to reflect the correct amounts of Real Property Tax Receivable, Real Property Tax, Due to LGUs (GF and SEF), Deferred RPT, Special Education Tax Receivable, Special Education Tax and Deferred SET.

We also recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare separate Abstract of Real Property Taxes for the collection of advance payments of property taxes which will be the basis of the Accounting Office for proper recognition of advance payments and discounts granted in the books.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Reorganize the Inventory and Disposal Committee, comprising permanent employees currently serving with the Municipality;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer/Property Officer to take appropriate action in maintaining Property Cards for all the PPEs of the LGU;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to maintain  Property Ledger Cards and reconcile them accordingly with the Property Cards maintained by the designated Property Officer;
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare an itemized schedule for each PPE account to determine the composition of each PPE indicating the description, cost, and date acquired; and
Begin the process of complying with the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account balances to ensure the accuracy and reliability of the assertions regarding the existence, condition, and valuation of the PPE accounts.
We further recommended that upon reorganization of the Inventory and Disposal Committee, the Local Chief Executive should ensure that:

A physical count of all properties will be conducted at least once a year to prepare the RPCPPE to be submitted to the Audit Team; and
Unserviceable properties of the Municipality will be inspected to prepare the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable. Properties (IRRUP) and the Waste Materials Report (WMR) to be submitted to the Audit Team.

We recommended the following measures to Management: 

Create an Inventory Committee that will be responsible in the conduct of the inventory of the Local Road Network System of the LGU;

For the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

For the General Services Officer to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components also using the prescribed format as mentioned in the above circular;

For the Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for each road and road components for every road network; and

For the management to prepare detailed action plan in the conduct of the inventory of local roads specifying the timeline and actions to be taken to address the issues. This should begin with the Municipal Engineering Office providing the cost segregation of road components for road projects.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Require the Municipal Assessor to determine the cause of delay on the completion of the required documents over the nineteen (19) parcels of land to properly address the issues which will fast track the processing of titles;

Direct the Municipal Assessor to coordinate with the Municipal Budget Officer regarding the needed budget allocation to complete the survey plans needed for the processing of titles;

Include in the annual budget the needed amount for the initiative to obtain land titles on lands that the LGU asserts ownership; and

Instruct the Municipal Assessor to legally document the ownership of untitled lots by obtaining a Transfer Certificate of Title (TCT) in the name of the Municipal Government of San Jacinto pursuant to Section 39 of PD No. 1445 in order to protect the interest of the LGU and to avoid future potential disputes.

We recommended and Management agreed to require the HRMO to:

Ensure that all Accomplishment Reports are approved by the department heads of the designated/assigned JO workers;

Require JO workers to quantify their daily accomplishments in their Accomplishment Reports;

Ensure compliance with the “No Work, No Pay” Policy stated in the Memorandum of Agreement. Coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to scrutinize the DTRs submitted by the JO workers before payroll preparation to accurately deduct absences for each cut-off period;

Submit the identification cards of all Job Order workers, along with three specimen signatures, for verifying the authenticity of their signatures on Accomplishment Reports, DTRs, payroll, and MOAs;

Provide justification for the different rates given to JO workers with the same designation, as well as for sudden rate increases;

Require the department heads in need of JO workers to submit a request to the Local Chief Executive. The request must include the number of JOs required, the specific services each JO will render, and justification for additional manpower;

Include job description or work specifications in the contracts between the LGU and JO workers. These descriptions should align with services requested by the department heads;

Evaluate tasks delegated to JO workers based on their accomplishments and assess the appropriateness of the number of JO workers per unit or office; and

Establish the necessary criteria, guidelines, and qualifications of JO workers. These should serve as the basis for determining rates for each hired JO worker.

We recommended and management agreed to require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, to:

Instruct the requesting departments to indicate the estimated unit cost and total estimated cost in the Purchase Request and refrain from using pencil in preparing the PR;

Ensure the proper filling out of Purchase Orders by indicating the Terms and Conditions of the payment and delivery of each procured goods;

Require each supplier to issue collection receipts for all goods purchased with issued charge sales invoices;

Instruct the Bids and Awards Committee to ensure that the delivery period in the RFQ, NTP, and PhilGEPS posting are all the same to avoid confusion and inconsistencies;

Require proof of actual expenses incurred for each operation by the PNP as the basis for financial assistance given to them;

 Require the MSWDO to attach the proof of identification or ID with three specimen signatures of the person authorized by the beneficiary to claim the assistance;

Compute the subsistence allowance based on actual services rendered to avoid issuance of Notice of Disallowance for erroneous computations for payments made;

Attach original Official Receipts for all petty expenses indicating the equivalent amount of actual expenses and the amount claimed;

Ensure the attachment of a copy of Special Order from the agency/department Head covering the assignment to hazardous/difficult areas in the Hazard Duty payroll as required by COA Circular No. 2012-001; and

Instruct the officers and employees claiming excess hotel accommodation expenses to provide certification by the agency head or authorized representative as absolutely necessary in the performance of an assignment.

We recommended and Management agreed to comply with the following measures:

Ensure the establishment of electricity connection and water supply for both the Moringa Production Center and RHU II as the immediate steps for the complete implementation of these two projects; 

Require the Municipal Engineer to submit the master plan, design plans and the overall program of works for the entirety of the Eco-Park project so that management can also prescribe timelines for the partial and ultimately full operability of the Eco- Park;

The Municipal Health Office to plan the temporary utilization of the RHU II building as a Barangay Health Center and allocate the assignment of personnel to effect as soon as the electricity connection and water supply have been established;

Require the Municipal Agriculture Office to coordinate closely with the Municipal Engineering Office to address the defects in the greenhouse, ensuring its full operational status. Also, establish maintenance schedule for the greenhouse to address future issues and ensure full functionality; 

Direct the Municipal Agriculture Office to designate personnel responsible for continuous supervision and maintenance of the greenhouse operations; and

Require the Municipal Agriculture Office, Municipal Engineering, Office and Municipal Health Office to provide a schedule outlining the steps to be undertaken to put each of the idle facilities to work and operate.

5. Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the difference in the balance of the Cash-Local Treasury between their Offices, submit their working papers/reconciliation documents to the Office of the Auditor, and prepare necessary correcting entries in the Agency’s books or cashbooks;
6. Direct the Municipal Treasurer, the Liquidating Officers and the collectors to deposit/turnover all future collections intact and not to retain portion of them pursuant to the aforementioned provisions; and
7. Strengthen internal control over collections, remittances and deposits and consider the promulgation and implementation of a policy in order to avoid retention of big amounts of money in the hands of the accountable officers.

8. Direct the Municipal Accountant to give preferential attention in the preparation and submission of the required BRS, maintain an updated SL per bank accounts, review the records relevant to the Cash in Bank account and effect necessary adjustments to correct the amount presented in the FS and other documents;
9. Require the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the Source Agencies on the status of fund transfers to the Municipality and close the accounts that have become dormant and revert back to the Source Agency or the Bureau of the Treasury, as the case maybe, if the said accounts represent excess of the expenses for the projects funded by NGAs and/or other Agencies; and
10. Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to prioritize the Cash in Bank accounts reconciliation to come up with the correct balances thereof as presented in the FS.

16. Analyze the affected accounts to determine to which funds the amounts are due and prepare necessary adjusting journal entries to reflect the correct balances of each account in their respective fund classification;
17. Prepare and maintain SLs for all the aforementioned reciprocal accounts; and
18. Conduct periodic reconciliation/analysis, preferably on a quarterly basis, of the reciprocal accounts “Due from/to Other Funds” to ensure that necessary adjustments in the books of accounts are made on time.

32. Explain the noted deficiencies in the submitted documents;
33. Prepare and submit the following: i. Supplemental LDIP and AIP which include the projects funded by the LGSF-SBDP NTF-ELCA; ii. Quarterly Report on Fund Utilization and Status of Program/Project Implementation using the prescribed format; and iii. Separate SLs for each beneficiary barangay and projects implemented; and
34. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to strictly adhere with the timing on withholding taxes and observe proper recording of accounts and ensure that the submitted DVs are supported with complete and properly filled-out documentary requirements.

35. Enjoin the LDRRM Council to closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund and ensure its optimum utilization;
36. Require the MDRRMO to prepare and submit the annual LDRRMFIP which includes under a separate caption, the list of PPAs charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years and specify and elaborate the details of its DRRM program for proper accounting, monitoring and audit of the LDRRMF;
37. Require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Budget Officer and MDRRMO to conduct annual reconciliation of their respective records on the utilization of LDRRMF to avoid inconsistent balances on their reports and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted accordingly;
38. Ensure in the succeeding years that the transfer of actual cash pertaining to the unexpended balances of the QRF and DRRMF-MOOE to the STF be made immediately at year-end. Also, facilitate the transfer of the unexpended MF-MOOE from the GF to TF immediately; and
39. Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to maintain separate RAAOs for LDRRMF to facilitate proper control and monitoring of the balances.

40. Require the LSB to ensure that prescribed planning and budgeting tools are properly prepared and submitted and effectively utilized. Also, the timelines in the planning and budgeting process are strictly observed as prescribed under the aforementioned Circulars;
41. Stop the practice of lump-sum appropriation and identify the specific PPAs with specific amounts during budget preparation;
42. Require the Municipal Budget Officer to stop the practice of charging prior year’s expense against current appropriation; and
43. Stop the charging and payment of MOOE which are not included in the list of expenses chargeable against the SEF and ensure that the SEF be expended solely and exclusively for expenditures provided under DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017 and its addenda.

44. Maximize the utilization of the 20 percent DF and implement the PPAs within the targeted time frame to achieve the social, economic and environmental outcomes essential in the attainment of the constitutional objective of a desired quality of life for all; and
45. Formulate well-defined procedures to enhance the monitoring and evaluation activities during project implementation, which includes among others, the coordination with the Municipal Engineer in monitoring the implementation of projects funded from the 20 percent DF to attain the optimal socio-economic development and environmental management outcomes which is the core of the fund allocation;
46. Moreover, we recommended that Management instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that the submitted DVs are supported with complete documentary requirements and direct the Municipal Budget Officer to prepare the RAAO of DF in its prescribed format and observe diligence in posting thereto to ensure proper monitoring of the balances.

47. Hasten the revision process of the 10-year SWM Plan of the Municipality and submit immediately to DENR-EMB for approval;
48. Strictly enforce and intensify the information campaign on “no segregation, no collection” policy among residents and consider imposing the prescribed fines and penalties for violators thereof;
49. Encourage and provide assistance to the remaining nine barangays to establish their own MRFs and re-establish those which are not functional. Likewise, require the allocation of fund for a sanitary landfill as a final disposal site for solid wastes; and
50. Allocate funds for the construction and operation of a sanitary landfill as a final disposal site for solid wastes.

51. Instruct the MPDC to facilitate the gathering of data and information needed for the creation of an updated and well-established GAD database to have an accurate and reliable basis in the planning and programming of PPAs as well as in the policy formulation in order to properly address the existing and emerging GAD issues and concerns;
52. Direct the GFPS and GAD key personnel to undergo capacity building programs and training on GAD to enhance their knowledge and build their competencies on GAD-related laws and international commitments, gender mainstreaming, gender analysis, gender-responsive planning and budgeting, and GAD-related tools like HGDG on the attributed budget to evaluate gender responsiveness of PPAs in the GPB;
53. Ensure that the PPAs charged to GAD fund are only those that would address the identified gender issues in the locality. The gender issues must be specific and supported by evidence such as sex-disaggregated data and gender analysis results; and
54. Direct the MSWDO/GAD Focal Person or the Concerned Office/s to refrain from expending beyond the appropriated budget per PPA and the Municipal Budget Officer to observe diligence in posting in RAAO to properly monitor the correct balances and to avoid overspending.

59. Management require the AOs in the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to strictly comply with the timely remittance/deposit of their collections as provided in Section 29, Volume I of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs. New stub of accountable forms must be issued to Collecting Clerks only when collections from prior stubs issued to them were already remitted in full;
60. The AOs exercise diligence in the preparation of RCD and recording of transactions in the cashbook to avoid complexity and the updating of their respective cash books; and
61. Increase the Fidelity Bond of the AOs in accordance with their respective total accountabilities and in compliance with Item 5.1 of Treasury Circular No. 02-009 dated August 6, 2009.

62. The Municipal Treasurer to update the RPTAR/Taxpayer’s index card based on the Assessment Roll and furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified list showing the names of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year;
63. The Municipal Accountant to observe and follow the correct accounting entries on the establishment, collection and recording of RPT and SET and reconcile the RPT/SET transactions and make necessary adjusting entries in order to reflect the correct amount of the affected accounts in the FS; and
64. Further, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor ensure that all officials and employees of the Municipality perform their duties and functions and take actions in accordance with the pertinent laws, rules and regulations.

69. Ensure that planned PPAs for SEF are optimally implemented/utilized for the efficient and timely delivery of targeted services and benefits to the constituents in accordance with the proper utilization of the fund;
70. Include the previous years’ unexpended balances, as well as the continuing appropriation, in determining the net amount available for appropriation;
71. Require the liquidation of financial assistance granted to DepEd Officials and refrain from granting the same. Instead, the Municipality can provide the supplies and materials needs of the agency/different schools in accordance with the guidelines, procurement law and accounting procedures to effectively monitor and determine whether or not the funds were utilized for its intended purpose; and
72. Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that proper accounts are used in the recording of the financial transactions and supporting documents thereof are complete.

73. Enjoin the LDRRMO to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures optimally related to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities;
74. Direct the LDRRMO to prepare the annual LDRRMFIP detailing all the PPAs to be funded in accordance with COA Circular 2012-002 to ensure proper evaluation of the same; and
75. Direct the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the MDRRMO to regularly prepare every month the Report on the Sources and Utilization of LDRRMF using the prescribed format in COA Circular No. 2012-002 and submit such report on or before the 15th day after the end of the month through the LDRRMC and LDC to the Audit Team in compliance with the reportorial requirements of the aforementioned COA Circular.

79. Submit the lacking required documents;
80. Assign a Liaison Officer who will be in charge of the submission of documents/follow-ups of official matters; and
81. Ensure strict compliance on the laws, rules and regulations on travelling expenses to avoid possible misuse of government funds.

90. Ensure that FTs to Barangays are supported with MOA and require them to comply with the guidelines before processing the claims and releasing the checks;
91. Direct the Municipal Accountant to effect correcting entry to set up receivable accounts while liquidation reports of the fund transfers are not yet submitted by the IAs; and
92. Send demand letters to the five Barangays for the immediate liquidation of the FTs.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management:

Create an Inventory Committee through the issuance of an EO. Subsequently, direct them to prepare the PIP for approval of the Local Chief Executive (LCE) and submit the same to the Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;

Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all PPE following the guidelines outlined in COA Circular No. 2020-006 and submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team; 

Direct the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to maintain Property Cards and PPELC, respectively and reconcile their PPE records; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit a lapsing schedule of all PPE, ensure monthly recognition of depreciation expense of all the PPE accounts and record the adjustments in the government equity account for the prior years’ depreciation expenses; 

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjustments in the books to properly classify the PPE accounts and correct all erroneous recording; and

Direct the Inventory Committee to exert utmost effort in conducting the activities relative to the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

