Instruct the Municipal Assessor to legally document the ownership of untitled lots by obtaining a Transfer Certificate of Title (TCT) in the name of the Municipal Government of San Jacinto pursuant to Section 39 of PD No. 1445 in order to protect the interest of the LGU and to avoid future potential disputes.

We recommended and Management agreed to require the HRMO to:
Ensure that all Accomplishment Reports are approved by the department heads of the designated/assigned JO workers;
Require JO workers to quantify their daily accomplishments in their Accomplishment Reports;
Ensure compliance with the “No Work, No Pay” Policy stated in the Memorandum of Agreement. Coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to scrutinize the DTRs submitted by the JO workers before payroll preparation to accurately deduct absences for each cut-off period;
Submit the identification cards of all Job Order workers, along with three specimen signatures, for verifying the authenticity of their signatures on Accomplishment Reports, DTRs, payroll, and MOAs;
Provide justification for the different rates given to JO workers with the same designation, as well as for sudden rate increases;
Require the department heads in need of JO workers to submit a request to the Local Chief Executive. The request must include the number of JOs required, the specific services each JO will render, and justification for additional manpower;
Include job description or work specifications in the contracts between the LGU and JO workers. These descriptions should align with services requested by the department heads;
Evaluate tasks delegated to JO workers based on their accomplishments and assess the appropriateness of the number of JO workers per unit or office; and
Establish the necessary criteria, guidelines, and qualifications of JO workers. These should serve as the basis for determining rates for each hired JO worker.

We reiterated our recommendations that Management:
Direct the Inventory Committee to facilitate the conduct of complete physical count of all the Municipality’s properties annually and prepare and submit the RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain property records for all PPE and undertake the required reconciliation of the Property and Accounting records thereafter;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare SLs and lapsing schedule for all PPE accounts and make the necessary adjustments to come up with the correct PPE accounts balances; and
Facilitate the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances through the implementation of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We reiterated our recommendations that the LCE:
Prioritize issuance of demand letters to all accountable officers and employees to immediately liquidate/settle their outstanding CA;
Require the Municipal Accountant to stop the practice of granting additional CA to those who have unliquidated CA and strengthen the operation of preventive and monitoring controls to ensure timely submission of liquidation documents and avoid undue accumulation of outstanding CA;
Fast track the recovery of the documents relevant to the long outstanding CA and conduct verification, analysis, make necessary adjusting entries and validation to determine the settlement/collectability and pursue collection, refund or liquidation, if warranted; and
Conform with the procedures and requirements set forth in COA Circular No. 2016-005 and immediately facilitate the request for write-off of dormant unliquidated CA.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Inventory Committee to complete the conduct of inventory count of all the local roads and prepare and submit the RPCLRN;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Inventory Committee with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects to facilitate the preparation of RPCLRN;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and maintain separate SLs/LRNLCs and LRNPCs, respectively, for local road projects and reconcile both records to ensure proper recording and control of the assets;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and submit the RLRN and Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component of road network, make necessary adjustments to correct the unrecorded depreciation expense as of year-end and provide proper and complete disclosure of the total road networks in the Notes to FS in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Conduct an in-depth verification of the Due to BIR, GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth accounts, perform reconciliation between the SLs and the Schedules of Remittances and remit immediately the withheld funds, if warranted, and;
Evaluate the current system of withholding and remitting taxes, premiums, contributions and other deductions to prevent under or over remittance thereof.

We recommended that the LCE:
Enjoin the LDRRM Council to closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund and ensure its optimum utilization;
Require the MDRRMO to prepare and submit the annual LDRRMFIP which includes under a separate caption, the list of PPAs charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years and specify and elaborate the details of its DRRM program for proper accounting, monitoring and audit of the LDRRMF;
Require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Budget Officer and MDRRMO to conduct annual reconciliation of their respective records on the utilization of LDRRMF to avoid inconsistent balances on their reports and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted thereon accordingly;
Ensure in the succeeding years that the transfer of actual cash pertaining to the unexpended balances of the Quick Response Fund (QRF) and DRRMF-Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses (MOOE) to the Special Trust Fund (STF) be made immediately at year-end. Also, facilitate the transfer of the unexpended Mitigation Fund (MF)-MOOE from the General Fund to Trust Fund immediately; and
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to maintain separate Registries of Appropriations, Allotments and Obligations (RAAOs) for LDRRMF to facilitate proper control and monitoring of appropriations, allotments and obligations under the said fund.

We recommended that Management:
Require the LSB to ensure that prescribed planning and budgeting tools are properly prepared and submitted, and effectively utilized. Also, the timelines in the planning and budgeting process are strictly observed as prescribed under the aforementioned Circulars;
Stop the practice of lump-sum appropriation and identify the specific PPAs with specific amounts during budget preparation;
Require the Municipal Accountant to observe accrual basis of accounting; and
Stop the charging and payment of MOOE which are not included in the list of expenses chargeable against the SEF and ensure that the SEF be expended solely and exclusively for expenditures provided under DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017 and its addenda.

We recommended that the LCE, through the Municipal SWMB:
Hasten the revision process of the 10-year SWM Plan of the Municipality and submit immediately to DENR-EMB for approval;
Strictly enforce and intensify the information campaign on “no segregation, no collection” policy among residents and consider imposing the prescribed fines and penalties for violators thereof;
Encourage and provide assistance to the remaining nine barangays to establish their own MRFs and re-establish those which are not functional. Likewise, require the Barangay officials and constituents for the strict compliance of the guidelines and criteria set under RA No. 9003; and
Allocate funds for the construction and operation of a sanitary landfill as a final disposal site for solid wastes.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the MPDC to facilitate the gathering of data and information needed for the creation of an updated and well-established GAD database to have an accurate and reliable basis in the planning and programming of PPAs as well as in the policy formulation in order to properly address the existing and emerging GAD issues and concerns;
Direct the GFPS and GAD key personnel to undergo capacity building programs and training on GAD to enhance their knowledge and build their competencies on GAD-related laws and international commitments, gender mainstreaming, gender analysis, gender-responsive planning and budgeting, and GAD-related tools like HGDG on the attributed budget to evaluate gender responsiveness of PPAs in the GPB;
Ensure that the PPAs charged to GAD fund are only those that would address the identified gender issues in the locality. The gender issues must be specific and supported by evidence such as sex-disaggregated data and gender analysis results; and
Direct the MSWDO/GAD Focal Person or the Concerned Office/s to refrain from expending beyond the appropriated budget per PPA and the Municipal Budget Officer to observe diligence in posting in RAAO to properly monitor the correct balances and to avoid overspending.

We reiterated our recommendation that Management require:

The Municipal Assessor to provide a copy of an updated Assessment Roll to the Municipal Treasurer which contains the list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed and the values of such properties on or before the 31st of December each year;

The Municipal Treasurer to update the RPTAR/Taxpayer’s index card based on the Assessment Roll and furnish the Municipal Accountant a duly certified list showing the names of taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year;

The Municipal Accountant to observe and follow the correct accounting entries on the establishment, collection and recording of RPT and SET and reconcile the RPT/SET transactions and make necessary adjusting entries in order to reflect the correct amount of the affected accounts in the FS; and

Further, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor ensure that all officials and employees of the Municipality perform their duties and functions and take actions in accordance with the pertinent laws, rules and regulations.

We recommended that Management:

Stop the practice of granting cash assistance to clients or person in the absence of complete documentary requirements. The submission of complete documentary requirements for each type of assistance are condition precedent to the payment;

Endorse the individuals seeking medical assistance to the RHU of the LGU for their disposition rather than providing them immediate cash assistance.  Only when the RHU has no available medicines for the client/patient, the medical assistance may be granted subject to the guidelines enunciated by the DSWD MC No. 11, s. 2019; and 

Prepare and issue a well-defined set of policies and guidelines governing the implementation of AICS program which must be aligned with the guidelines issued by the DSWD governing the grants of AICS. The policies and guidelines must contain the following:

Kind of financial assistance (burial, transportation, medical, educational, food, shelter and others);

Limitations on the amounts given per kind of financial assistance;

Criteria in granting the financial assistance and the documentary requirements for each particular case; and

Well defined roles and responsibilities of the officials processing requests.

We recommended that the Municipal Government endeavor to further improve its process in recording and overall management of RPT and SET Receivables through the following strategies:

Require the Municipal Assessor, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to strictly follow the proper process in recording of RPT and SET Receivables as prescribed under Section 248 of RA No. 7160 and Section 20, Volume I of  New Government Accounting System Manual for Local Government Units;
Require the Municipal Accountant to credit accounts RPT and SET Receivables upon collection pursuant to Section 24 and 25, Volume II of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System;
Cause the posting of a Notice of Delinquency in the Payment of Real Property Tax at the main entrance of the Municipal Hall and in other publicly accessible place and conspicuous place in each barangay of the municipality in accordance with Section 254 of RA No. 7160; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain a subsidiary ledger pertaining to RPT and SET Receivables.

We reiterated previous years’ audit recommendations that the Local Chief Executive instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to: 

Maintain individual subsidiary ledger for all accounts, as required under Sections 111 and 114 PD No. 1445; 


Exert diligent efforts to locate the necessary supporting documents to substantiate the LGUs recorded obligation and to determine the exact ageing of the liability accounts; 


Reclassify capitation fund and guaranty deposits accordingly;


Balances of fund transfers after the completion of the programs or projects be fully liquidated; and


Distribute the all barangay and provincial share from RPT and SET in accordance with RA 7160.


We also recommended that accounts payable which has been outstanding for two years or more may be reverted to the unappropriated surplus of the general fund provided that there is no actual claim, administrative or judicial has been filed.  However, unliquidated balances of accounts payable under the trust funds shall in no case be reverted unless the purposes for which these funds were created have been accomplished. 

Ensure that the Journal Entry Voucher for reversion of liability accounts be properly supported with the following:

List of available records and extent of validation made on the accounts; and

Certification and reasons why the books of accounts/records, financial statements/schedules and supporting vouchers/documents cannot be located.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and BAC Secretariat to post all NOA, contract, or purchase order in the website of the LGU, if any, or any conspicuous place in the premises of the PE and GPPB online portal for Emergency Procurement under the Bayanihan Act for information purposes and to require the submission of the mandatory documentary requirements from the concerned suppliers including explanations/justifications on the deficiencies noted; 

Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant, in coordination with MDRRMO and MSWDO, to submit the list of affected families and proof of receipt of distribution of relief goods and other supporting documents;

Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to require the suppliers to issue sales invoice upon payment of goods by the LGU pursuant to the provisions of Revenue Memorandum Circular No. 2-2014.

Ensure that the remaining balance of Bayanihan Grant be utilized before the lifting of State of Calamity which was extended until September 30, 2021.


Instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to prepare adjusting or correcting entries on erroneous recorded transactions, and observe the use of proper accounts prescribed under the Government Accounting Manual for accurate and reliable presentation of accounts in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer, in coordination with the OIC-Municipal Accountant, to identify the insurable properties of the LGU;   

Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to prepare the Property Inventory Form and submit the same to the GSIS as the basis for the assessment of general insurance coverage of all insurable assets of the LGU using the forms prescribed in COA Circular No. 2018-002;


Require the Municipal Budget Officer to provide appropriation for the payment of premiums of all insurable assets of the LGU; and

Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to secure the property insurance of non-insured government properties with the GSIS.

We recommended that Management:
Implement immediately the continuing appropriation portion CO of the unimplemented GAD projects and activities;
Require the concerned official to comply with the mandatory minimum allotment for GAD which is five percent of the Agency’s total budget, including both Internal Revenue Allotment and other local income sources;
Require the GAD Focal Person to observe compliance with the submission of the copy of GPB to the DILG Regional Office on or before March of the preceding year for appropriate review and approval. DILG-approved GPB must include a certificate of approval from the DILG Regional Office and must be incorporated in the year’s annual budget to be enacted by the Sanggunian; and
Require the GFPS to create a local GAD code and facilitate establishment of VAW desk at the Barangay level.

We recommended that Management strictly comply with the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Roads Asset Management System prescribed in COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015.
We further recommended that Management:
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network, and disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the total road network system;
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer, in the absence of General Services Officer, to maintain a Report of the Local Road Network and Road Map and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components;
Create an inventory committee to conduct the physical count and prepare the Report on the Physical Count of the Road Network System; and
Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to transfer the local from the Registry of Public Infrastructure to the General Fund which will form part of the Property, Plant and Equipment of the LGU under Road Networks account pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant and/or Acting Municipal Treasurer to:
Revert to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund the balance of  Accounts Payable  amounting to ₱329,752.47, pursuant to Section 98 of PD No. 1445;
Reclassify the receipt of retention money from two (2) contractors with a total amount of ₱97,970.01, from bail bonds payable to Guaranty/Security Deposits Payable. Then, release the retention money to the contractors concerned provided that projects were completed in accordance with approved plans and specification, pursuant to Section 62.1 of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of RA No.9184;
Reclassify the refund of BIR amounting to ₱37,794.11 from Due to BIR account to Accounts Payable.  The amount be released to the supplier concerned accordingly;
Request a certification from the GSIS that there was no outstanding arrearages of the LGU as of December 31, 2021. When arrearages are confirmed to have been settled, the amount of ₱397,704.78  are to be reverted to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund;
Release the unremitted provincial share and barangay share from the collection of Special Education Tax and Real Property Tax, respectively. Likewise, unutilized balance of ₱1,152.96 from the financial assistance given by the  Province of Pangasinan for the rehabilitation of the municipal  building be reverted to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund;
Refund the  unutilized balances of fund transfers to the source agencies with a total amount of ₱119,042.14, unless otherwise stated in the MOA;
Reclassify the balance of fund transfer from LGU Mangaldan, from Due to NGAs to Due to LGUs account. Unutilized balance of ₱993.83 be refunded to LGU Mangaldan unless otherwise stated in the MOA;
Revert to the  unappropriated surplus of the General Fund all unutilized funds from projects and programs funded from the share of Excise Tax and PCSO;
Revert to the General Fund the amount of ₱450.55 for the unutilized balance of LGUs activity “Kilos Asenso”  to close the Due to Other Fund account; and
Release the balance of retention money to the contractors concerned provided that projects were satisfactory completed.
Ensure that adjustments, reversions of unutilized funds,  releases/payments of payables to supplier/contractors, remittance of RPT/SET to province and barangays, and others, be  properly documented to support the validity and correctness of transactions or adjustments.
To address the issue on undocumented Other payable accounts of ₱434,191.21, that has been in the books of accounts for more than six (6) years, we recommended that the Local Chief Executive request for write-off and/or adjustment of account balances from the COA, supported by the following, pursuant to Item No. 10 of COA Circular No. 97-001 dated February 5, 1997:
List of available records and extent of validation made on the accounts; and
Certification and reasons why the books of accounts/records, financial statements/schedules and supporting vouchers/documents cannot be located.

We recommended that Management undertake the following actions in the disposal of unserviceable/obsolete property and equipment:
Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to report all unserviceable property and equipment of the LGU in the IIRUP and to ensure that the said report be duly accomplished;
Create a Disposal/Appraisal Committee to conduct inspection and manage the disposal process of unserviceable properties;
Require the Acting Municipal Treasurer to ensure that the unserviceable/obsolete property and equipment be disposed pursuant to Section 79 of PD No. 1445 ;and
Instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant and Acting Municipal Treasurer to determine the value of the ambulance and Isuzu mini dump truck in the preparation of IIRUP.

